{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604586/1945090301/0109.xml":{"full_text":"13 Ships Due Today\nWith 10,000 Veterans\nFrom European Area\nB* the Associated Press.\nThirteen transports bringing\nhome more than 10,000 servicemen\nfrom Europe are scheduled to dock\ntoday at New York, Boston and\nNewport News, Va.\nArmy units and troop designa\ntions include:\nAt New York\u2014(Aboard General\nPatrick) 2,292 troops, no listing\navailable.\n(Aboard Huddleston) 427 soldier\npatients. (Aboard Marine Raven)\n3,095 troops, including the 59th\nChemical Maintenance Company;\n1,035th, 2,853d Engineer Gas Gen\nerator Detachments; 95th Medical\nGas Treatment Battalion; 167th\nGeneral Hospital; Headquarters and\nHeadquarters Detachment of 228th\nOrdnance Base Depot; 3,041st,\n3.042d, 3,043d Quartermaster Graves\nRegistration Companies; 214th,\n217th Military Police Companies;\n597th Port Company; 465th. 620th\nMilitary Police Escort Guard Com\npanies; 45th Medical Supply Pla\ntoon, Aviation; 196th Medical Dis\npensary, Aviation.\nlADoara 1 >oiusa m. aicoM) 11\ntroops, undesignated units. (Aboard\n.James Parker) 3,004 troops diverted\nfrom the Pacific, including 154th.\n156th. 157th, 158th, 160th and 227th\nLaundry Detachments; 3,657th,\n3,713th, 3,993d, 3,733d, 3,994th Quar\ntermaster Truck Companies; 490th,\n697th Medical Ambulance Compa\nnies; 12th, 153d. 299th and 298th\nArmy Postal Units; 15th Major Port;\n143d, 144th, 441st, 442d, 443d Mili\ntary Police Detachments; 864th\nQuatermaster Fumigating and Bath\nCompany; 84th Engineer Camou\nflage Battalion; 723d Medical Com\npany; 2.818th Engineer Detachment;\n3,093d Engineer Welding Detach\nment. (Aboard George M. Bibb)\n745 troops, including the 828th Con\nvalescent Center; Infantry Division\nReorganized Detachments. (Aboard\nJames L. Breck) 21 troops, undesig\nnated units. (Aboard Southwest\nVictory) 28 trooop6 for rotation.\n(Aboard Arthur Huddle) 15 troops\nfor discharge.\nAt Boston: (Aboard Patrick Whe\nlan) 36 miscellaneous troops.\nAt Newport News: (Aboard Likes,\ndue yesterday), 30 troops, undesig\nnated units. (Aboard Chew, due yes\nterday) 26 troops, undesignated\nunits. (Aboard Lanham) 14 troops,'\nundesignated unit*.\nThe following Army units arrived\nyesterday:\nm.\" v u ttilic.> UC\nWolf), 12 reassignment troops.'\n(Aboard Alexander Lillingtom, 408\ntroops, including 204th Infantry re\nplacement detachments; Headquar\nters and Base Service Squadron of\nthe 419th Air Service Group and:\nReassignment. Troops. Aboard\nJames G. Blaine), 457 troops, un\ndesignated units. (Aboard Felix\nGrundy, 415 troops for reassign\nment. (Aboard Samuel Ashe), 1.191\ntroops including the 197th Quarter\nmaster Laundry Detachment, 14th\nMilitary Police Escort Guard Com\npany and Detachment D, and 438\neasuals.\nAt Boston (aboard Brandon Vic\ntory): 1,964 troops including Army\nservice forces unit package zone of\nthe interior detachment and escort\npersonnel, surplus personnel and\nmiscellaneous personnel; 112th Liai\nson Squadron, Post Detachment,\n36th Infantry Division, and Post\nDetachment, 45th Infantry Divi\nsion. (Aboard Jonathan Edwards),\n754 troops including 81st Chemical\nMortar Battalion and miscellaneous\nand surplus personnel.\nAt Newport News (aboard Gen\neral Morton): 3,839 troop6 including\nelements of the 711th, 713th. 721st,\n739th, 679th and 702d Air Materiel\nSquadron; 69th Depot Supply Com\npany, 1st, 2d and 3d Air Cargo Re\nsupply Squadrons: 65th, 66th and\n82d Airdrome Squadrons: 164th\nGeneral Hospital, 16th Station Com\nplement Squadron, 1372d Ordnance\nDepot Company, Aviation, and the\n321st Transport Cargo Mail Squad\nron. (Aboard Chapel Hill Vic\ntory), 1,934th troops including ele\nments of the 40th Army Air Forces\nbase unit.\n'nuudiu vjrcxi. uiiuuu troops, I\nincluding elements of the 678th En\ngineer Company: 523d Engineer\nMaintenance Company; 140th Medi\ncal and Evacuation Hospital; 597th\nMedical Ambulance Company; 5th\nMedical Auxiliary Surgical Group;\n635th Quartermaster Laundry Com\npany; 355th Quartermaster Truck\nCompany: 627th Port Company;\n2,713th Engineer LE Company;\n84th Engineer Battalion of 823d\nMilitary Police Company; 4.030th\nand 4,032d Quartermaster Truck\nCompanies; 840th Quartermaster\nSupply Company; 202d Quartermas\nter Car Company: 215th Ordnance\nHM Company; 569th Petrol Prod\ncuts Laboratory; 865th Quartermas\nter Fumigation and Bath Company;\n3.097th Quartermaster Laundry\nCompany; 59th Quartermaster Sales\nCompany, and 107th Port Marine\nMaintenance Company. (Aboard J.\nLawson) 457 troope, undesignated\nunits. (Aboard Page) 2 troops.\n2,500 Pacific Veterans\nLand in San Francisco\nSAN FRANCISCO, Sept. 3 </P).\u2014\nTwo transports docked here yester\nday. bringing 2,500 veterans from\nthe Pacific.\nA \u201cwelcome home boat\" filled with\ncheering women met them at the\nGolden Gate and escorted them up\nthe bay.\nThe San Francisco Port of Em\nbarkation band played the veterans\nBOiiVMO.\nThe homecoming soldiers also were\ntreated to a steak dinner\u2014all part\nof welcome ceremonies planned by\nMaj. Gen. Homer M. Croninger, port\ncommander.\nBy this afternoon the entire group\nis expected to be bound for reception\nand separation centers near their\nhomes.__\nv Stalin\n(Continued From First Page.')\nBritain,\u201d Premier Stalin asserted.\n\u201cThey also inflicted most serious\ndamage on our country. Therefore\nwe have a special account of our\nown to settle with Japan.\u201d\nThe Soviet home radio opened its\nnews broadcast today with a de\ntailed account of the Japanese ca\npitulation aboard the United States\nbattleship Missouri. The descrip\ntion emphasised the role played by\nthe United States in the Pacific war.\nA cold rain dampened the pro\nspects for the holiday, but victory\nmeetings were held in thousands of\nfactories, schools and clubs. Gorki\nstreet, Moscow\u2019s main thoroughfare,\nwas decorated elaborately. Moscow\nsubways will remain open until 2\nam. tomorrow to enable late cele\nbrants to get home.\nBERLIN VISITORS A group of members of Congress on a special mission to Europe\nposed for this picture on >he balcony of the German Chancellery in Berlin recently. Standing\nwhere Hitler made many of his speeches are, left to right, Representatives Wickersham, Democrat,\nof Oklahoma; Weiss, Democrat, of Pennsylvania; Huber, Democrat, of Ohio; Horan, Republican, of\nWashington; Merrow, Republican, of New Hampshire; Feighan, Democrat, of Ohio; Dondero,\nRepublican, of Michigan. Carnahan, Democrat, of Missouri. \u2014AP Photo.\nLabor, Lauded for Role\nI\nIn War, Looks Ahead\nI\nTo Jobless Battle\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nLabor drew praise from military\nand congressional leaders today for\nthe part it played in winning the\nwar. while labor leaders and others\nreminded that the battle against un\nemployment also must be won.\nAmong the statements issued as\nthe Nation observed the Labor Day'\nholiday were these:\nRobert P. Patterson, Underscore-'\ntary of War\u2014\"For their contribution:\ntoward victory, the men and women'\nin our war industries deserve the!\nhighest commendation.\u201d\nGen. H. H. Arnold, commanding!\nthe Army Air Forces\u2014\"The workers\n(vho stayed at their jobs, and j\nastounded the world in spite of the'\nstresses and strains of wartime liv\ning, are entitled to the gratitude of\nthe entire Nation.\"\nucn. jicuD i.. utvera, command\ning the Army Ground Forces\u2014\"Now\nthat peace is at last bringing home\nthe combat soldiers, we must all\ncontinue the teamwork which\nbrought us success in war.\u201d\nGen. Brehon B. Somervell, com\nmanding the Army Service Forces\u2014\n\"The record of the Army Service,\nForces in arming and supplying,\nmore than 8.000,000 men is equally;\nthe record of labor.\u201d\nSecretary of the Treasury Vinson\n\u2014\u201cMay we, the people of this coun\ntry, have the Intelligence and the\nenergy to wage the peace and the\nreconversion as completely and as,\nsuccessfully as we waged total war.\u201d I\nSenator Wagner, Democrat, of\nNew York\u2014\u201cThe people\u2019s sacrifice in\nwar implies and demands a people\u2019s\npeace The' voice and aspira-!\ntions of labor should be heard at\nthe peace table, as well as in plan\nning for full postwar employment\nand prosperity at home.\"\nSenator Myers, Democrat, of Penn\nsylvania\u2014 \u201cThe United States can\nprovide a job for every man and\nwoman who wants to work. And it\ncan do so by maintaining the full;\nproductive output of the war. In:\npeacetime this will mean not only a\njob for all but also a 50 per cent\nincrease in our standard of living.\u201d j\nm limp i'iui at) pi voiucuv Vi me\nCIO \u201cIn Its unparalleled war\nachievements America has shown a\ncapacity for organization and pro\nduction that should assure the full\nemployment of our people after the\nwar in creating unparalleled proa\nperity for all. But, with reconver\nsion already under way. there are\nmany tragic signs that selfish priv\nilege and governmental inertia are\nobstructing the fulfillment of that\npromise.\u201d\nSenator Mead, Democrat, of New\nYork\u2014\u201cThe sudden capitulation of\nthe Japanese last month presents\nthe leaders of this Nation with a\nsolemn obligation to see that the\nworkers of the country do not suffer\nin the period of reconversion.\u201d\nGeorge Meany, AFL secretary\ntreasurer\u2014\u201cWhen we proclaim our\nallegiance to free enterprise, as op\nposed to Communism. Socialism or\nFascism, we mean free enterprise\nas it ought to be and as we intend\nto have it be\u2014a system under which\nthe profit motive is not reserved to\nthe owners of industry. Labor,\nwhich produces our wealth, is en\ntitled to its full and fair share of\nthat wealth.\u201d\nEdward N. Scheiberling, national\ncommander of the American Legion\n\u2014\u201cWe have won the war but now we\nmust win the peace. To do that we\nmust first win the battle of employ\nment. This is a battle that will\nchallenge the minds of labor, in\ndustry and Government.\u201d\niv. d. i uuinu, picfiiucni/ ui Luc\nCIO United Automobile Workers\u2014\n\"Congress must decide quickly\nwhether we are in the future to have\nan economy of scarcity and hunger\nand job fear, or whether we are\nto take the necessary steps to meet\nthe shock of reconversion and the\nfuture agony and waste caused by\nrecurring economic depressions.\u201d\nJean A. Brunner, commander Vet\nerans of Foreign Wars\u2014\"The bick\nerings between labor and industry\nmust cease and the spirit of broth\nerly love and common sense must\nreign, so that our fighting men and\nwomen can look upon those who\nstayed at home and produced the\nvital materials of war as partners\nand brothers and not as rivals for\nemployment.\u201d\nSidney Hillman, chairman of the\nCIO Political Action Committee\u2014\n\"We can beat unemployment and\npoverty. We have the power to do\nit. Let us resolve on this Labor Day,\n1945, to make it a victory over all\nour enemies\u2014domestic and foreign\u2014\nthe greatest of them being poverty.\u201d\n127 Captured at Guam\nFreed at Kobe Camp\nBy the Asiocisted Freu.\nYOKOHAMA, Sept. 3.\u2014Captured\nat Guam three and a half years\nago, 127 American civilian workers\nhave been freed by the comman\ndant of the Mount Futatabi Camp\nat Kobe, occupation forces here\nwere informed\u2014but most of them\nhave chosen to remain in the camp\nuntil American troops arrive.\nHirohito\n(Continued Prom First Page.)\nworry\" about securing enough lum\nber to rebuild 300,000 houses by the\nend of the year.\nUnemployment and food prob\nlems resulting from demobilization\nof Japanese forces ana repatriation\nof Japanese nationals abroad also\nwill be of \"serious proportions,\" the\nDomel news agency warned.\nThe dispatch, recorded by the\nPederal Communications Commis\nsion, said the homeland\u2019s present\npopulation of 74,000,000 is expected\nto be swelled to more than 80,000,000\nby the influx.\n\"With the importation of food\nstuffs suspended,\" the broadcast\nadded, \u201cit is believed it will be im\npossible to maintain the present\nquota of rationing of staple food\nstuffs.\" Domei estimated, too. that\napproximately 4.000.000 adults will\nbe jobless.\nDraft\n'Continued From First Page.l\nsure a proper sharing of combat\nduty? In other words, are you\nspecifically endeavoring to bring\nhome those men who have had over\nseas service and, where necessary,\nreplacing them with men who have\nnot served on foreign soil?\nWants Estimate of Needs.\n\"3. Does your department have\nany way of ascertaining the specific\nnumber of men you will require for\nthe Army of Occupation? If so,\ncould you give me what your esti\nmate might be as to the size of this\narmy?\n\"4. What steps have been taken\nby your department to inform fami\nlies of servicemen of the policies\nwhich are to be carried out in con\nnection with discharge of men now\nin service? I make this inquiry!\nin view of the fact that letters com-1\ning to me seem to indicate a wide- i\nspread lack of understanding and\nstate of confusion among the gen\neral public.\n\"5. Do you look with favor to any\nextent on a policy which would per\nmit youngvnen within a year of col\nlege graduation to be given any\nkind of preference toward dis\ncharge for the purpose of complet\ning the necessary requirements to\nprepare themselves for their chosen\nvocation?\n\"6. Is your department finding\nitself swamped, if I may use the\nexpression, by discharged procedure\nand, if so, have proper steps been\ntaken to elleviate this condition and j\nprovide sufficient staff to bring\nabout, prompt handling of the!\nnecessary papers for men whom you j\ncan approve for discharge?\u201d\nOccupation\n(Continued From First Page.)\nforthwith to cease hostilities,\" and\ndisarm.\nHis proclamation agreed that\nJapan would abide by Potsdam dec\nlaration restrictions, which specify\noccupation until lasting peace is\nassured, and require removal of bar\nriers to free speech and religion.\nRussell Brines, veteran Associated\nPress Tokyo correspondent, reported\nthat many of Japan\u2019s intelligentsia,\nfreed of Japanese militaristic rule,\n\u201cconsider American forces almost as\nliberators.\"\nTokyo's Yomiuri Hochi urged edi\ntorially that proportional represen\ntation be adopted to make scheduled\nelections next January \u201cfair,\u201d and\nurged greater powers for Japan's\nHouse of Representatives.\nA tremendous show of Allied mili\ntary power was spread over and\naround the Japanese dignitaries as\nthey signed the formal surrender\naboard the Missouri Sunday. Above\nthe cloud cover. Foreign Minister\nMamoru Shigemitsu and his retinue\ncould hear nearly 2,000 Allied planes\ncircling overhead. Around them\nlay a vast array of Allied warships;\nand ashore was the vanguard of oc\ncupation troops expected soon to\ntotal half a million.\nJaps Stiffly Impassive.\nShigemitsu was the first to sign,\nand Gen. Yoshljiro Umezu added\nhis signature for the imperial staff.\nNine other Japanese stood by, un\ninformed or silk-hatted, all stiffly\nimpassive.\nThe 30-minute ceremony began\nwith the slow, clear words of Gen.\nMacArthur: \"We are gathered here,\nrepresentatives of the major war\nring powers, to conclude a solemn\nagreement\nAll topflight American generals\nand admirals of the Pacific were\nthere, wearing khaki, without neck\nties, without decorations or ribbons.\nAllied signers assembled in Admiral\nChester W. Nimitz's cabin, filing out\non deck in order of their rank.\nGen. MacArthur signed first, using\nsix pens. The first he gave to Lt.\nGen. Jonathan Walnwright, hero of\nCorregidor; the second, to Lt. Gen.\nSir Arthur Percival, British com\nmander at Singapore in 1943. Ad\nmiral Nimits gave one of the two\npens he used in signing for the\nUnited States to Admiral Halsey.\nAdmiral Sir Bruce Fraser signed for\nthe United Kingdom.\nWalnwright returned immediately\nto the Philippines, where he received\nthe surrender of Japanese Lt. Gen.\nTomoyuki Y&mashita today.\n56 District Area Men\nAre Brought Home\nFrom Europe\nThe names of 56 men of the j\nWashington area arriving from1\noverseas at Boston. New York, New\nport News, Va., and Florida, were\nannounced today.\nArriving at Boston Saturday\naboard the Santa Maria were:\nCapl. Theodore N. Btrdsong, 3811 N.\nNinth street, Arlington. Va.; 1st Lt. Layton\nD. Munson. 714 S. Twenty-second street.\nArlington: T/8ergt. Robert J. Alexsnder,\n380(1 N Washington boulevard. Arilngton.\nAlso 1st Lt. Joseph N. Rldgely. Jr.. Upper\nMarlboro. Md.: Capt. Frank M. Bertzbough.\n308 Upper College terrace. Frederick, Md\nT/4 Obed B. By. 236 E Second atreet.\nFrederick, and Pfc Charles V. Coodey. 407 1\nBrowning terrace, Takoma Park. Md.\nThirty-six District men are ex- j\npected in New York Wednesday on\nthe Sea Scamp. They are:\n8/Sergt Ralph B. Gilmore. 1021 Fifty\nfirst street 8.E. Corpl. Jerome King. 14\nDefrees street N.W Corpl. Phillip L.\nThomas, 4S23 Hunt place N E Pfc. John\nE Dean. 24 B street N.E Corpl Harry T\nHumphries. 950 Florida avenue N W\nCorpl. Herman L Jones, address not\ngiven; Pfc John E. Bailey. 880 Forty\nfourth street N E\nAlso Pfc. Joseph P. Booth. 1531 Sixth\nstreet N.W.: Pfc. John Powell. 30 K street\nNE Pvt. Louis W Ferguson. 2220 G\nstreet N.W T/3 George E Seheytt. 1921\nSeventeenth street S.E.; Corpl. Clarence\nE. Norment. Wardman Park Hotel: Pfc\nJohn T. Spalding. 2508 North atreet 8.E\nLt. John C. Hinkle. 8enate Office Build\ning: Pfc Neal Harris. Jr., 65THI Sheriff\nroad NE.\nAlso Pfc. Clifton Tyler. 2602 Bowen\nroad EE.: Pvt Charles T Brown. 2aJ2\nThirteenth street NW.: Pvt. Clarence E\nFord. 1346 Twenty-eighth street N.W.;\nPfc. Clyde G. Lesaane. 812 Vernon atreet\nN.W Pfc. Calvin A. Pollard. 1743 Swann\nstreet N.W.; Pfc. Morris M. Hall. 1013\nNew Jersey avenue S.E. Pfc. James Jack\nson. 1502 Kingman place: Pic. Harry M.\nLayne, 963 Twenty-sixth atreet N.W.\nAlso Pfc. Clarence L. Medley, 4529 Dtx\nstreet N.E.: Pfc. Charles Chandler. 728\nNineteenth street N.E.: Pfc. Ralph C. Cole\nman, 251 I street N.W.: Pfc. Walter 81ms.\n502 Secona street N.W.; T/4 Bethunt Rol\nlinson, 116 Sixteenth street N.E; T,5\nHarmon K. Pair. 734 Park road N.W.: Pfc.\nHenry J. Brown. 338 W street;. T/Sergt.\nwilliam B Case!, 530 Somerset place; Pvt\nRudolph V Davis, 20 Myrtle atreet N E\nAboard the James G. Osin, which ar\nrived In New Terk yesterday, were:\nPfc. Clarence B. Allen. 623 L street N.E\n8/Sergt. Jesse N. Hawkins. 69 Myrtle\nstreet N.B.: Sertt. James E. Brown. 345\nI street 8.W.; Corpl. Thuraton Harrison.\n1724 D street HW.: Pfc. William A. Poin\ndexter. 80 O street N.E.: Pvt. Earl O.\nWashington, 134 P street N.W.; and War\nrant Officer O. g.) John H. Hunter, 3335\nBrothers place 8.E\n\u2022nuuMi& uuuija uuiiuuK in hl new*\nport News, Va., were:\nPvt. Melvin H Fltggerald. 3814 North\nSeventeenth etreet. Arlington. V\u00bb lit\nSent. William R. Bennett. United States\nSoldiers' Home: S/8ergt, Vincent Picco.\nHarriet avenue. Beat Pleasant. Md Corpl\nJohn H. Pierce. 121 Seventeenth street\nS.E.. Pfc. res B Fox. 311 North Market\nstreet. Frederick. Md Pfc. Henry T\nWoychak. 708 North Jefferson street. Ar\nlington. Va\nT/5 Wesley H. Davin of 7007 Ninth\nstreet N.W. is expected September\n10 at Newport News aboard the\nPhillip De Neve.\nPvt. Eugene E. Adams. 37, of 1412\nNorth Utah street, Arlington. Va..\nrifleman, has arrived at Miami\nBeach, Fla., after eight months in\nEurope. Sergt, Victor W. Newton\nof 1400 Twenty-ninth street S.E., of\nthe 760th Tank Battalion, arrived\nby plane from Europe and has re\nported at Camp Blandlng, Fia.\nGreen\n>Continued From First Page.!\nbill to broaden coverage of old age\nand aurvivors insurance.\nMr. Green said that although\nthere were important problems to be\nsolved he did not envisage a major\npostwar depression.\nRefers to Prophets of Gloom.\n\"I know there are prophets of\ngloom who see nothing but discour\nagement and failure ahead,\" he\nsaid. \"They point to the undeniable\nfact that America was not prepared\nfor peace, that reconversion is pro\nceeding too slowly, that unemploy\nment may reach the alarming total\nof seven or eight million by next\nspring and that Congress has not\ntaken steps to provide for human\nneeds during the transition period\nfrom war to peace. On the basis\nof these adverse conditions they for\nsee a major postwar depression.\n\"The American Federation of La\nbor does not share these pessimistic\nviews. We do not believe In crying\n\u25a0fire!\u2019 in a crowded theater. We\ndo not intend to stampede the Na\ntion into panic.\u201d\nMr. Green said he looked for co\noperation among workers and vet\nerans, adding:\n\"Any one who tries to divide la\nbor and tHe veterans and set than\nagainst each other is an enemy of\nAmerican democracy. For it is just\nas essential for labor and the vet\nerans to stand together and work\ntogether to win the peace as it was\nto win the war.\u201d\nRadio Listeners Urged\nTo Express Preferences\nE? the Associated Press.\nRadio audiences should tell the\nstations what they like or don't like\non the air, says Paul Porter, Federal\nCommunications Commission chair\nman.\n\"The channels of the ether by\nwhich these programs reach you are\nyours,\" he said last night on a Co\nlumbia Broadcasting System pro\nt gram, \"They don\u2019t belong to the\nnetwork, the stations or the PCC.\u201d\nThe station, Mr. Porter added,\nwill be responsive to the public\u2019s\nwishes.\n\"I think the management of our\nbroadcasting systems will agree that\nby and large the public receives over\nthe air not necessarily what It wants\nbut what it doesn\u2019t about.\u201d\nTruk and Palau Japs\nSign Surrenders to\nYank Commanders\nBr the AinocUted Prat.\nGUAM. Sept. The Truk and\nPalau groups of once heavily forti\nfied islands in the Carolines and\nPagan and Rota in the Marianas\nsurrendered yesterday to American\ncommanders, the Navy announced.\nThe surrenders involved more than\n100,000 Japanese.\nVice Admiral George D. Murray,\nNavy commander of the Marianas\nand veteran of Solomons carrier ac\ntions, accepted surrender of Truk by\na Japanese delegation aboard the\nlight cruiser Portland. There are\npossibly 60,000 Japanese in the Truk\ngroup.\nLit. Gen. Sadae-Inoue signed the\nsurrender of the Palau islands In\nthe wardroom of the destroyer\nAmick. ^Marine Brig. Gen. F. O.\nRogers, Waco, Tex., island com\nmander of nearby American-held\nPeleliu, signed for the United States.\nThere are estimated to be 44,000\nJapanese nationals in the Palau\ngroup.\nPagan, 180 miles north of Saipan,\nwas surrendered at ceremonies\naboard a destroyer to Commodore\nVernon F. Grant of Hattiesburg and\nMeridian, Miss., and Mobile, Ala., by\nMaj. Gen. Umahachi Amau. Pagan\nhas 2.238 Japanese army and navy\npersonnel.\nAttending the Pagan ceremonies\nwere Comdr. A. A. Allen of Alex\nandria, Va., and Lt. Craten Allen.\nJr., of Hudson, Ohio.\nRota, Japan's last remaining out\npost in the Marianas, also capitu\nlated with its 3,980 military per\nsonnel.\nComdr. Allen is on military leave\nfrom the editorial staff of The Star.\nDispatches last Friday said he had\nwitnessed the surrender at Marcus\nIsland.\nSoviet Chess Stars Lead\nAmericans in Radio Match\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 3 \u2014Chess stars\nof the Soviet Union today held a\nlong lead over the United States\nteam as the international radio\nmatch between the two countries\nwent into its second half.\nYesterday the Russian experts\nscored eight points against the\nAmerican team's two. Herman\nSteiner of Los Angeles, who tied\nfor third place in the United States\nchess championship last year, was\nthe only American to win, defeating\nIgor Bondarevsky.\nAlbert S. Pincus, playing Andrea\nLilienthal, and Reuben Pine, who\nwas matched with Isaac Boleslavsky,\neach scored draws to win another\npoint for the United States. Seven\nother members of the 10-man Amer\nican team were defeated.\nPlay during the first lap of the\ncontest, which opened Saturday, re\nquired a total of 16 hours. Moves\nare being sent by radio. The com\npetition continues today.\nMr. Steiner, starting alowly in\nyesterday\u2019s game, consumed 45\nminutes in his first seven moves,\nleaving only two more minute* play\ning time to complete the 14 addi\ntional moves which brought him\nvictory.\nPhilippines\nContinued From First Page\nentered the United States high\ncommissioner\u2019s residence at this\nsummer capital, but was ordered\nto remain standing. Later he was\nallowed to sit down for the signing.\nThe document which gave up all\nJapanese land, sea and air forces In\nthe Philippines was signed by Yam\nashita and Admiral Okochi. ranking\nJapanese naval officer, at 12:05 p.m.\n(11:05 p.m Sunday, United States\nEastern wartime).\nThe event had been delayed more\nthan three hours while awaiting the\narrival from Japan of Gen. Wain\nwright In order that he might per\nsonally accept the surrender.\nLeavey Signs for U. S.\nMaj. Gen. Edmond H. Leavey,\nchief of staff to Lt. Gen. W. D. Styer,\ncommander of American forces in\nthe Western Pacific, signed the doc\nument for the United State*. Gen\nWalnwright and Gen. Percival stood\non each side of him.\nYamashita and his party, which\nincluded four generals and two ad\nmirals. were later taken in charge\nas prisoners of war for delivery t\u00ab\nnew Bilibid Prison.\nThey entered American 33d Divi\nsion lines on Northern Luzon yes\nterday after a two-day journey from\ntheir mountain hideout and were\nbrought here by plane.\nGen. Styer opened the session, an\nnouncing that Gen. Leavey would\nact for him. Maj. Gen. W. A. Wood,\njr., then read the terms and said:\n\u201cYamashita, you have heard read\nthe instrument of surrender where\nby you surrender all Japanese\nland, sea and air forces in the\nPhilippines. Are you ready\nto sign the surrender documents?\u201d\nYamashita replied: \u201cI am.\u201d\nThe signing followed.\nThree pens used were given to\nGen. Walnwright, Gen. Percival and\nGen, Styer.\n\u201cGreatest Day* of My Life.\"\nAfter the ceremony, Gen. Wain\nwright said: \"I am without words\nto tell the thrill of seeing the sur\nrender aboard the Missouri and I\nhave had an equal thrill just now\nin seeing the imperial command\nbow and bend to the United States.\nDuring the first five months of this\nwar we were handled rather se\nverely and lacked the force to com\nbat these people.\n\"The shoe is on the other foot\ntoday. Yesterday and today were\nthe greatest days of my life.\u201d\nGen. Perclval observed with quiet\nemotion: \"Today retribution has\ncome\u2014a great gratification to me\nand all those officers and men who\nserved under my command.\u201d\nBefore leaving for Bilibid, the\nJapanese turned over their cere,\nmonial swords and sidearms to Col.\nGeorge Bishop.\nPilot Killed in Collision\nOver Richmond Identified\nBy the Associated Press.\nSEYMOUR JOHNSON FIELD, N.\nC., Sept. 3.\u2014Flight Officer Lewi C.\nKirk, 30. of Harrisburg, Pa., was\nidentified as the victim of a two\nplane collision Saturday morning\nover Richmond, Va.\nCol. D. B. Howard, commanding\nofficer of the Seymour Johnson\nField, said both planes were Amy\nfighters and on a training mission\nat the time of the collision.\nThe pilot and only occupant of the\nether plane, Ool. Howard said, para\nchuted to safety.\nA\nBishop Urges Speedy\nAction to Meet Drop\nIn War Employment\nBy thf Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, Sept. 3.\u2014The Nation\nshould not hesitate to use \u201cemer\ngency measures\u201d to meet the situa\ntion arising from the elimination of\nthe Government its the \"one cus\ntomer for nearly half our produc\ntion,\u201d the Most Rev. Francis J. Haas,\nBishop of Grand Rapids, said today.\n\"Now and without delay,\u201d he said\nin a prepared sermon to a Labor\nDay mass sonsored by the Catholic\nLabor Alliance, \"Congress should\nenact into law the Murray full em\nployment bill, increase unemploy\nment compensation up to a national\nlevel of $35 per week for a period\nof at least 26 weeks: increase\nthe present hourly minimum from\n40 to 75 cents; broaden the Social\nSecurity Act to include health in\nsurance, and appropriate adequate\nsums for public works and\nUnited States Emloyment Service.\"\nFirst FEPC Chairman.\nBishop Haas, first chairman of\nthe Fair Employment Practices\nCommittee, based his plea on a. quo\ntation from St. Paul, \"Bear one\nanother\u2019s burdens and so you will\nfulfill the law of Christ,\" and as\nserted:\n\u201cThus we repudiate the doctrine\nthat industry' is to be operated\nmerely to make money for those who\ncan make it. We condemn the short\nsighted policy of maintaining a\nregime of scarcity\u2014either through\ncartels, or price fixing, or the re\nstrictive practices of certain labor\nunions\u2014in order that the private\ninitiative of a few may be rewarded\nat the expense of all the rest. And\nwhile we insist that private initia\ntive be maintained, we insist that It\nopirate to the production of enough\ngoods and services for all the people.\nTruly ours is an emer\ngency and we may not hesitate to\nuse emergency measures. Our situa\ntion is no different from that of the\npeople In a flood area. They do not\ndebate the niceties of this or that\nmeasure. They have but one\nthought, to save themselves. In like\nmanner our Congress may not close\nits eyes to the fact that what is\nat stake is the very life of the\nNation.\u201d\nPraises Bargaining Charter.\nBishop Haas termed the labor\nmanagement charter signed recently\nby representatives of the United\nStates Chamber of Commerce and\nCIO and A PL leaders as a frank\nrecognition by \"one national body\nof manufacturers\u201d of labor's right\nto collective bargaining.\n\u201cLet us not minimize this point,\u201d\nhe continued. \"There is no need\nto ulk about co-operation, joint\naction and working together in in\ndustry for a common purpose\nunless employers regard the right\nof workers to organize democrat\nically and to deal collectively\nthrough their own representatives,\nas 'finished business.\u2019\nPolice Seek Parents\nOf Abandoned Infant I\nLittle \"Billy Doe\u201d slept peacefully\nin his crib at Gallinger Hospital\ntoday while police continued a\nsearch for his parents. The infant\nwas found Saturday in a suitcase at\nthe rear ot the 1400 Mock of Harvard\nstreet N.W.\nNow weighing 6 pounds 9 ounces\nand as healthy as can be, Billy is the\nidol of nurses who think the blue\neyed blond infant is \"awfully sweet.\u201d\nThe hospital has had many calls\nfrom persons who would like to\nadopt Billy, but such negotiations\nmust be taken up with the Board of\nPublic Welfare.\nNurses said the baby would re\nmain at the hospital until the wel\nfare board decides whether to place\nhim in an orphanage or sanctions\nhis adoption.\nTourist Attitude\nOf Navy Forces\nIn Japan Halted\nBj the Associated Press,\nWITH UNITED STATES 3d\nFLEET, Tokyo Bay, Sept. 3.\u2014Naval\noccupation forces were Instructed\nofficially today to use \u201ca firm hand\"\nin dealing with the Japanese but\nto avoid \"needless oppression.\"\nThe instructions, indicative of of\nficial desires to abolish the holiday\ntourist attitude displayed by some\noccupation forces, were published\nfor guidance of all naval occupa\ntion units.\nMany Americans ashore obviously\nhave been bent on sightseeing,\nsearching for souvenir shops and\nwelcoming opportunities to converse\nwith English-speaking Japanese.\nThe new Instructions direct that\n\u201cthe Japanese will not be allowed\nto forget that they are defeated\nand are paying the penalty for their\naggression and treachery.\nProperty rights will be respected.\nLooting and acts contrary to stand\nards of human decency will not be\ntolerated.\"\n39 D. C. Area Veterans\nReceive Discharges\nAt Fort Meade Center\nThe names of 38 men from the\nWashington area honorably dis\ncharged from the Army at Fort\nMeade Friday through 8unday were\nannounced today.\nThey are:\n_ \u00a3TtC'aude Cooper. 374, Gram atreet\nJf E T/4 Lloyd Pollard. 620 Third atreet\nfenO. George N lletael. 406 Eighth\nstreet 8.W: Pfc. Harvey Tonic, 1328\n*l*hth atreet N w Ke Geor_f N pamer,\n132 Third street S.E.: T/4 Robert N. Red\nmond. 501 Upland place. Alexandria. Va.:\nPyt. Johnnie H. Thomas, 327 First atreet,\nAlexandria\nA1f\u00b0 T Mlles- 507 Ninth\nstreet S.W.: T/4 Joaeph Liberty. 1138\nM\u00b0,r\u00ab street N.E Sertt. Bereh A. Kearns.\n2114 H street N.E.: 8/Sergt. Ragar L. Ly\nerly. 4608 Twenty-ninth atreet. Mount\nMd M/Sertt. Harry W. Caje,\n2128 N Pollard street. Arlington: Pvt.\nRobert N Houehln. 725 Fifth atreet N.E\n8ergt. Albert D. Gawlt. 1112 Greenwood\navenue. Takoma Park. Md.; Sertt. Themi\nstoeolee Plaekoat, 7217 F street HE.; Pfc.\nPrank W Wilson. 3607 Norris place. Alex\nandria: Pfc. George L. Greene. 2907 8.\nNasn street. Arlington.\nAlso T/5 James A. Murphy, 400 Evarts\n*\u2018r\u00abt N.E: 8 /Sertt. James H. Culver.\n3210 Ninth place 8.E.; T/5 Oerald F.\nFitzgerald. 3004 Yoat place N.E.: 8er*t\nThomas W. Scott, 2704 Thirty-sixth\nstreet N.W T/3 Bernard 8. Beall. 3513\nBunker Hill road, Mount Rainier. Md.:\n8/Sergt. Wilbur L. Barr. 810 Whittier\nSlaee N W T/4 Albert W Browning. 1309\n.tax street. Alexandria: T/8ertt. Norman\nW. Wach. 1919 Port Davis place 8.E\nS/8ergt. Fred Shaw. 307 Avenue E. Dis\ntrict Heights. Md.: Pfc. Jack K. Lefeure.\n17 Ames street N.E.; Pfc. Albert C. Hodges.\nRoute 2. Box 239. Washington.\nAlso Corpl. Roy E. Keller. 1915 N. Fairfax\ndrive, Arlington: Sergt. Russell w. Clum.\n1339 Madison street N.W Corpl Joseph\nM Ryan, 1820 Clydeadale place N.W.;\nPfc. Raymond L. Jones. 504 8. Henry street,\nAlexandria: 8/Bent. John W. McCullock.\n17 Fourteenth street S.E.: Sent Joe H\nGibson. 2000 H street N W Corpl Arnold\nC. Key. 4213 Seventy-first avenue. Land\nover Hills. Md.: Corpl. Harvey W. Bright.\n507 8. Henry street, Alexandria: T/3 John\nB. Milliner. 3123 Twelfth atreet NE:\nT Sergt. Ernest M. Waters. 1220 Nine\nteenth atreet N E T/Sergt. Joaeph G\nRaaaainsky. 1928 Fourteenth street S B.\n500,000th Veteran\nLands at Newport News\nEt the Associated Pres*.\nNEWPORT NEWS. Va\u201e Sept. 3.\u2014\nAmong the 9.643 soldiers to debark\nhere yesterday from the European\ntheater was the 500,000th soldier to\nhave debarked at the Hampton\nRoads Port of Embarkation since\nits activation. June 15. 1942. He\nwas Corpl. Leon R. Carman of\nOsceola, Nebr.\nCorpl. Carman was with the 83d\nAirdrome Squadron of the 9th Army\nAir Force. A cook, he went over\nseas December 2, 1943, and served\nthrough the Normandy invasion and\nthe Battle of the Bulge.\n700 Letters in Year\nSeven hundred letters have been\nreceived in a year by a 21-year\nold Ayrshire, Scotland, wife from\nher husband in Burma and she\nwrites to him every day, her letter\npostage bill totaling over $80 so far.\nArmy to Ask Funds\nTo Expand Capital's\nWater Facilities\nThe Army Engineer Corps an\nnounced today It will ask Congress\nfor construction funds to increase\nthe Washington area's water\nsupply.\nNew facilities would be built soon\nin the vicinity of the Dalecarlia\nand McMillan filtration plants and\nwould consist of additional mixing\nand sedimentation basins, six new\nfilters, new pumping stations, dear\nwater storage basins and trans\nmission mains.\nEstimated cost of the construc\ntion work for the ensuing year Is\n$317,000.\nThe Engineers Corps also said\nplans and specifications for con\nstruction improvements for the\nWashington channel would be ready\nabout the first of the year. The\nestimated cost to complete pier and (j\nyacht harbor construction there is V\n$2,500,000.\nIt was also announced that an\nimprovement of Hoskins Creek, Va..\nis being studied to provide con\ntinuous navigation facilities for\nsmall work boats and pleasure craft.\nIt Is expected that several other\nprojects designed to benefit small\nboats in the lower reaches of the\nPatuxent, Potomac and Rappahan\nnock Rivers will be ready for con\nstruction after the first of the year,\nArmy engineers said.\nPolio Areas Cautioned\nDDT Use Is Experiment\nAmerican families in polio epi\ndemic areas were cautioned today\nby the National Foundation for In\nfantile Paralysis, Inc., that the use\nof DDT in flighting infantile paral\nysis is still in the experimental\nstage and that its value, if any, most\nlikely will not be known for sev\neral months.\nDr. Don W. Gudakunst, medical\ndirector of the foundation, said \"the\ntremendous amount of newspaper\nand radio publicity given to DDT\nmakes it important that every one\nunderstand the role of this power\nful insecticide in the fight against\ninfantile paralysis.\"\nDDT solutions have recently been\nsprayed over limited portions of\nRockford, ID.; Savannah, Ga.: Pat\nerson, N. J\u201e and New Haven, Conn.\nPurpose of the spraying, financed\nout of a $25,000 grant by the Na\ntional Foundation, is to kill all flies\nin a particular area, study the re\nsults with respect to infantile paral\nysis and compare them with data\nfrom unsprayed areas.\nFoundation officials said it *ould\nbe months before definite findings\ncould be made as to whether flies\nplay any part in the spread of the\ndisease.\nMonument\nt Continued From First Pagc.t\nblood Miss Martin. \"Where\u2019s break**\nfast?\"\n\u2018T\u2019U Jump out this window if I\nhave to walk back down,\u201d Mrs. Lytle\nchimed in, but Miss Martin said she\nwould be glad to walk back for a\nhotel room and Juicy steak.\n\"The sad pan of it all is that we\npaid our dimes to ride the elevator,\"\nthe girls moaned.\nThe five climbers ran to 3,809,311\nthe number of persons who have\nwalked up since the monument was\nopened October 9, 1888. More than\n20,000,000 persons have been\nthrough the shaft, but most have\nused the elevator.\nAdolph Boyack. 70. of Buffalo,\nN. Y., wanted to Join the youngsters\non the stairs and insisted he could\nmake it despite his years. A guard\ntalked him out of it. for which he\nlater appeared grateful after view\ning the perspiring faces of the\nyouths.\nTrie MODE Important Mens Comer F Street at Eleventh-\"J\nHold your \u201cBULL SESSIONS\u201d\nat The Mode for Your...\n(AMpos\nc[?TteS\nIf the dormitory walls could\ntalk, they'd certainly tell a\nlot of stories. And some of\nthe fit for the ear sessions\nwould be how The Mode is\n\"in the know\u201d for the smart\nest clothes for campus\nminded young men. Come in\nand let's talk it over.\nRichard Prince Shetland Suits\u2014i-48.00\nt Richard Prince Covert Topcoats_40.00\nSport or Casual Jackets_$25 and 29.50\nGray Flannel or Covert Slocks-10.50 to 15.75\nMcGregor Sport Shirts_7.95 to $10\nMcCurroch Clan Plaid Ties_2.50\nMcGregor Sweaters---5.95 to 12.50\nWhitehall Shoes.7.50 to 11.50\nM i\nj\n3\nI 'V v \u2018\u20194\n\u2022I-\nME trepeRta* 0144 Street at Eleventh vz\n\u2022*7\nJ\n.V\nn\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u2014\u2014\u2014e\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014<e\u2014__. r*\n^P","height":"31652","width":"22540"}}
